            "description": "",
            "details": "<p><em>Nehr-i Sūs</em><span>: It flows above the city called </span><em>İstanca</em><span> (Istanja / Écija, Spain). The inhabitants of the villages along its banks engage in abundant agriculture. It descends from the </span><em>cibāl-i Şuġūre</em><span> (Mountains of Shughur / Sierra Morena) toward </span><em>Cühelācinān</em><span> (Jūhala–Cinān? a region in al-Andalus), then passes by the cities of </span><em>Yebāt</em><span> (Ébora / Evora?) and </span><em>Ḳurṭuba</em><span> (Córdoba). To the east, it reaches </span><em>İşbiliyye</em><span> (Seville); to the west, it passes by </span><em>Ṭırmāna</em><span> (Tirmana?) and finally flows into the </span><em>Baḥr-i Muḥīṭ</em><span> (the Atlantic Ocean). In this river, just as in the </span><em>Dicle</em><span> (Tigris) near Basra, tides (</span><em>medd u cezr</em><span>) occur. It is said that during the tidal period, the water advances seventy miles, and even then its water does not become salty, but remains fresh. The more the moon’s light increases, the greater the rising tide becomes. Ships set out for their destinations at this favorable moment. Sometimes, Frankish ships enter this river from the </span><em>Baḥr-i Muḥīṭ</em><span> (Atlantic) and sail as far as </span><em>İşbiliyye</em><span> (Seville). [translation]</span></p>",
            "end": 1599,
